{
  "doc_id": "28940",
  "text": "At Alano, P. capdevilensis has a very low abundance across the MECO and is absent in the upper organic-rich layers directly postdating the event (Fig. 3) , i.e. during eutrophication of surface waters [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Dissolution of Planorotalites could have influenced our data, because its lowest abundance occurs in intervals with high values of the fragmentation index [CITATION_3] . In the organic-rich layers above the MECO interval, foraminiferal tests show marked signs of dissolution and assemblage preservation deteriorates [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . However, foraminiferal preservation remains uniform throughout the pre-MECO and MECO intervals and is better than in the organic-rich levels, with tests without signs of dissolution [CITATION_6] .",
